<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-110-588  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 110 588.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Feb 27 1989 n527 p38(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Computing challenge in fluid dynamics.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Van Nostrand, Jim.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A NASA Ames Research Center report and two industry analysesreveal that the costs of computational fluid dynamics (CFD)research are declining, while the quality and quantity of data areincreasing, but more sophisticated software and more powerfulcomputers, design tools and development tools are needed.andP;  Thepresentations were made at the American Institute for Aeronauticsand Astronautics annual Aerospace Sciences Meeting.andP;  The technicalchallenges involved in CFD applications are going to requirecomputations that must be performed teraflop rates for upwards of100 hours at a time.andP;  About 1,000 times the current availablecomputing power would be necessary to achieve practical CFDsimulations.andP;  Several of the necessary technological developmentsto enable CFD research into specific problems are brieflydescribed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Research and DevelopmentAerodynamicsHydrodynamicsRequirements AnalysisComputational ComplexityApplicationsGoals and Objectives.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>